<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1440,193,346]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,336,193,217]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 14.0–23.5. Forewings light buff or beige throughout or with area between veins Sc and radius with ecru or brownish gray scaling in fresh specimens. Within forewing lobes, veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1424,1433,242,256]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">5</subScript>
, M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[217,226,274,288]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">3</subScript>
, Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[278,287,274,288]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">1</subScript>
, and Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[394,403,274,288]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">2</subScript>
, likewise traced with darker brownish gray scaling in fresh specimens. Hindwings brownish gray, body. Antennae, legs, and body light buff. Head with brownish gray to ochraceous basal scales. Abdomen with longitudinal brownish gray middorsal and subdorsal lines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1441,385,634]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,366,385,409]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Life History.</emphasis>
Larvae are stem and shoot borers of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lam.) Small. This" authorityName="Small. This" baseAuthorityName="Lam." box="[818,1368,386,410]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Eupatorium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="capillifolium">
<emphasis box="[818,1132,386,410]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Eupatorium capillifolium</emphasis>
(Lam.) Small. This
</taxonomicName>
plant occurs throughout most of 
<collectingCountry box="[510,670,418,442]" name="Bahamas" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
archipelago, except for the extreme southeastern portion (
<collectingRegion country="Bahamas" name="Inagua" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Great Inagua</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[297,518,450,474]" name="Turks and Caicos Islands" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Turks and Caicos</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Correll, D. S. &amp; H. B. Correll" box="[545,857,450,474]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" refId="ref7088" refString="Correll, D. S., and H. B. Correll. 1982. Flora of the Bahama Archipelago: (Including the Turks and Caicos Islands). J. Cramer; Hirschberg, Germany. 1692 p." type="book" year="1982">Correll and Correll 1982</bibRefCitation>
). Young larvae feed in the shoots but re-enter the lower stem and roots as they mature. As in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[786,922,482,506]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Hellinsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorias">
<emphasis box="[786,922,482,506]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">H. chlorias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, reddish longitudinal bands may be present and the circular anal plate bears a pair of thorn-like projections. The larvae are distinct from the latter species in having a patterned head with the sculpted adfrontal sclerites and epicranial suture bordered by a contrasting pale, smooth area (
<bibRefCitation author="Matthews, D. L." box="[748,943,578,602]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" refId="ref7316" refString="Matthews, D. L. 2006. Larvae and pupae of Nearctic Pterophoridae: A synopsis of life histories, morphology, and taxonomy (Lepidoptera: Pterophoroidea). Unpublished PhD Dissertation. University of Florida; Gainesville. 959 p." type="book" year="2006">Matthews 2006</bibRefCitation>
). As in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Meyrick" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[1032,1167,578,602]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Hellinsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chlorias">
<emphasis box="[1032,1167,578,602]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">H. chlorias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, larvae pupate within the stem gallery.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
